Use `defineConfig` from `@playwright/test` and set `use` options globally or per project. Here's a minimal `playwright.config.ts` that meets your requirements:

```ts
import { defineConfig, devices } from '@playwright/test';

export default defineConfig({
  testDir: './tests',
  fullyParallel: true,
  projects: [
    {
      name: 'Chromium',
      use: {
        ...devices['Desktop Chrome'],
        headless: true,
        viewport: { width: 1280, height: 720 },
        ignoreHTTPSErrors: true,
        consoleLogFilter: (msg) => {
          // Fail on errors/warnings if needed — here we just log them
          if (msg.type() === 'error' || msg.type() === 'warning') {
            console.error(`[${msg.type()}] ${msg.text()}`);
          }
        },
      },
    },
  ],
  timeout: 30000, // 30 seconds per test
  expect: {
    timeout: 10000, // 10s for assertions
  },
  reporter: 'list',
});
```

Notes:
- `timeout: 30000` sets the test-level timeout.
- `consoleLogFilter` lets you intercept and optionally fail on console messages (you’d add `throw new Error()` inside if strict mode is desired).
- To *fail* on any console error/warning, use:
  ```ts
  context.on('console', (msg) => {
    if (msg.type() === 'error' || msg.type() === 'warning') {
      throw new Error(`Console ${msg.type()}: ${msg.text()}`);
    }
  });
  ```
  inside `test.beforeEach()` or a custom fixture.

Combine `page.goto()` with `waitForLoadState('networkidle')`, then use `await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' }).waitFor()` (or similar) to wait for specific elements.

Example:

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('loads dynamic form after AJAX', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('/form');

  // Wait until network is idle (no outstanding requests for 500ms)
  await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');

  // Now wait for the dynamically loaded element
  const submitButton = page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' });
  await submitButton.waitFor({ state: 'visible' });

  await expect(submitButton).toBeVisible();
});
```

Best practices:
- Prefer `waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded')` if `networkidle` is too slow (e.g., long-polling).
- Avoid `setTimeout` — always use Playwright’s built-in waiting (e.g., `waitFor`, `expect(...).toBeVisible()`).
- `getByRole()` is WCAG-friendly and resilient: it uses accessibility tree, reducing brittle `class`/`id` selectors.

Use `page.route()` to intercept the POST request and fulfill with mocked JSON, ensuring the response mimics your backend’s success shape.

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('submits form and shows success message', async ({ page }) => {
  let formSubmitted = false;

  // Intercept API call and mock response
  await page.route('**/api/submit-form', async (route) => {
    const request = route.request();
    if (request.method() === 'POST') {
      formSubmitted = true;
      await route.fulfill({
        status: 200,
        contentType: 'application/json',
        body: JSON.stringify({ success: true, message: 'Form submitted!' }),
      });
    } else {
      await route.continue();
    }
  });

  await page.goto('/contact');

  // Fill form
  await page.getByLabel('Your name').fill('Jane Doe');
  await page.getByLabel('Email address').fill('jane@example.gov');
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Send message' }).click();

  // Assert mock was called and success shown
  await expect(page.getByText('Form submitted!')).toBeVisible();
  expect(formSubmitted).toBe(true);
});
```

Tips:
- Use `getByLabel()` for accessibility — matches `aria-label`, `label` text, or `placeholder`.
- Always `fulfill()` or `continue()` — omitting both hangs the request.
- Route handlers are removed automatically after test unless registered in `beforeEach`.

Use `page.goto()` with `waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded'` (or `'load'`) and then `page.title()` inside an assertion. Here's a minimal example using `@playwright/test`:

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('page title loads correctly', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org', { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' });
  const title = await page.title();
  expect(title).toBe('Welcome | Agency Example');
});
```

Best practice: Avoid `wait(5000)` — instead, rely on Playwright’s auto-waiting for actions (e.g., `await page.getByRole('button').click()`) and use `expect(...).toBeVisible()` or `expect(...).toHaveText()` which poll until ready.

