```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('submits form', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('/contact');

  // Prefer role-based locator if submit button has accessible role
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' }).click();

  // Or, if button lacks accessible name but has a label:
  // await page.getByLabel('Submit form').click();

  // Or, if no accessible name/label, use test-id (best practice):
  // await page.getByTestId('submit-button').click();

  await expect(page).toHaveURL('/contact?success=true');
});
```

**Why avoid `page.click()`?**
- `page.click()` uses CSS selectors and bypasses accessibility semantics
- It does not wait for actionability (focus, visibility, stability) as robustly as locators
- Locators like `getByRole()` and `getByLabel()` include built-in retry logic and align with WCAG 2.2 AA

**Pro tip:** Use `test-id` attributes for test stability:
```html
<button data-test-id="submit-button" type="submit">Submit</button>
```

Define a custom fixture using `test.extend()` in a `fixtures.ts` file (or directly in your test file):

```ts
// fixtures.ts
import { test as baseTest } from '@playwright/test';

export const test = baseTest.extend<{ loggedUser: string }>({
  loggedUser: async ({ page }, use) => {
    await page.goto('/login');
    await page.getByLabel('Email').fill('user@gov.example.org');
    await page.getByLabel('Password').fill('secure_password_123');
    await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Log in' }).click();
    await expect(page).toHaveURL(/.*dashboard/);
    await use('user@gov.example.org');
  }
});

export const expect = test.expect;
```

Then use it in your tests:
```ts
// my-test.spec.ts
import { test, expect } from './fixtures';

test('dashboard shows user name', async ({ page, loggedUser }) => {
  await expect(page.getByText(loggedUser)).toBeVisible();
});

test('logout clears session', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Log out' }).click();
  await expect(page).toHaveURL('/login');
});
```

**Best practices:**
- Use `test.extend()` for reusable setup/teardown
- Clean up with `afterEach` if needed (e.g., clear localStorage) inside fixture
- Pass only what your test needs (e.g., `loggedUser: string` instead of full `page` context)
- Fixtures are *per-test* by default — use `test.describe.configure({ mode: 'serial' })` for shared fixtures if absolutely necessary (rarely recommended)

Here's a minimal, WCAG-focused Playwright test using `@playwright/test` best practices:

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('page title contains Accessibility', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/accessibility');
  await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded');

  const title = await page.title();
  expect(title).toContain('Accessibility');
});
```

Key points:
- `waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded')` ensures DOM is ready before checking title
- Use `page.title()` — no locators needed for `<title>`
- Prefer `expect(...).toContain(...)` over strict equality for resilience
- All imports come from `@playwright/test` only

For WCAG compliance testing, extend with axe-core:
```ts
import { AxeBuilder } from '@axe-core/playwright';

await new AxeBuilder({ page }).analyze();
```

Use `getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit Application' })` — it's WCAG-compliant and resilient to markup changes:

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('submits form with accessible label', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/application');

  const submitButton = page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit Application' });
  await submitButton.click();

  // Verify navigation to confirmation page
  await expect(page).toHaveURL(/confirmation/);
});
```

If multiple buttons have 'Submit' in their accessible name:
- Add more specificity: `{ name: 'Submit Application', exact: true }`
- Or chain with context: `page.getByRole('form').getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit Application' })`
- Avoid `getByText()` — it ignores ARIA and screen reader semantics

Best practice: Always prefer `getByRole`, `getByLabel`, or `getByAltText` over CSS selectors for accessibility-first testing.

Configure `test.use({ strict: true })` in your Playwright config (`playwright.config.ts`):

```ts
import { defineConfig } from '@playwright/test';

export default defineConfig({
  use: {
    strict: true, // Throws error if selector matches multiple elements
    actionTimeout: 5000, // Fail fast on slow elements
  },
});
```

Then in tests:
```ts
test('uses unique aria-label', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/forms');

  // This will FAIL if two elements have aria-label="Submit"
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' }).click();
});
```

Why strict mode matters for WCAG:
- Ensures selectors resolve to exactly one element → encourages unique labels
- Prevents flaky tests caused by ambiguous selectors
- Aligns with SC 4.1.2 (Name, Role, Value) by promoting distinct accessible names

Note: `strict: true` applies globally; you can override per-test with `test.use({ strict: false })` only when absolutely necessary (e.g., testing duplicate components for a11y regression).

Use `getByLabel` to locate the input by its accessible label, `fill()` to type into it, and `expect().toBe()` to assert the value. Avoid deprecated `page.fill()` and `page.getAttribute()` in favour of locator-based APIs.

Example test (TypeScript, using `@playwright/test`):

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('fills first name and verifies', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('/contact');
  await page.getByLabel('First Name').fill('Alex');
  await expect(page.getByLabel('First Name')).toHaveValue('Alex');
});
```

Key points:
- `getByLabel('First Name')` uses accessible labels (WCAG 2.1 & 2.2 compliant if labels are present)
- `fill()` is actionability-aware (waits for element to be stable, visible, enabled)
- `toHaveValue()` is the recommended assertion for input/textarea values
- No `force: true` needed unless bypassing interactivity intentionally

If the label is missing, fix the markup (e.g., add `<label for="...">`) rather than using brittle selectors.

After `page.goto()`, use `await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle')` to ensure all network requests (like XHRs, fonts, images) have settled before asserting UI state. This is more reliable than `domcontentloaded` for dynamic apps.

Example:

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('navigates and waits for full load', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('/dashboard');
  await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');

  // Now safe to assert elements present after async content
  await expect(page.getByRole('heading', { name: 'Welcome' })).toBeVisible();
});
```

Alternative: `await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded')` for earlier readiness (when JS doesn’t affect what’s visible).

Avoid fixed `setTimeout()` — it’s flaky and slows tests unnecessarily.

Best practice: Combine with locator timeouts in `defineConfig()`:

```ts
// playwright.config.ts
import { defineConfig } from '@playwright/test';

export default defineConfig({
  timeout: 30000,
  use: {
    actionTimeout: 5000,
  },
});
```

Use `getByRole('dialog')` with an optional `name` match, then assert visibility. Playwright automatically waits for actionability, so no extra `waitForSelector()` needed.

Example:

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('opens modal with correct accessibility', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('/settings');

  // Click triggers async modal
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Delete Account' }).click();

  // Wait for modal to appear (Playwright waits up to default timeout)
  const modal = page.getByRole('dialog', { name: 'Confirm Deletion' });
  await expect(modal).toBeVisible();

  // Verify heading inside
  await expect(modal.getByRole('heading', { level: 2 })).toHaveText('Are you sure?');
});
```

Notes:
- `getByRole('dialog')` relies on `role="dialog"` or native `<dialog>` element (WCAG 2.1 & 2.2 compliant)
- If the modal lacks an accessible name, add `aria-label` or `aria-labelledby` — Playwright requires it for `getByRole('dialog', { name: '...' })`
- Avoid `locator.isVisible()` without `expect()` — use assertions for automatic retry

Fixing markup (if missing):
```html
<div role="dialog" aria-labelledby="modal-title">
  <h2 id="modal-title">Confirm Deletion</h2>
  …
</div>
```

Here’s a robust Playwright test using TypeScript, `@playwright/test`, and WCAG-aligned practices:

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('checkbox is unchecked by default', async ({ page }) => {
  // Navigate to the form page and wait for full load
  await page.goto('/accessibility/form-example');
  await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');

  // Use role-based locator for the checkbox — more robust than selector-based
  const checkbox = page.getByRole('checkbox', { name: 'Subscribe to newsletter' });

  // Assert initial unchecked state
  await expect(checkbox).not.toBeChecked();

  // Optional: verify label association for screen readers (SC 1.3.1)
  const label = page.getByLabel('Subscribe to newsletter', { exact: true });
  await expect(label).toHaveAttribute('for', expect.anything());
});
```

Key best practices:
- Use `getByRole()` for accessibility-aware locators (SC 4.1.2 compliance)
- Prefer `waitForLoadState('networkidle')` over hardcoded waits
- Avoid `page.isChecked()` — it’s deprecated; use `expect(locator).toBeChecked()`
- Use `networkidle` only if the page doesn’t rely on delayed dynamic content; otherwise, prefer `domcontentloaded` or a specific condition

For fixtures (e.g., logging in), use `test.beforeEach` with `playwright.fixtures`, not global variables.

Playwright’s **auto-waiting** and **explicit waiting** eliminate the need for `sleep()` or `setTimeout`. Here’s how to fix flaky tests:

✅ Do this:
```ts
await page.goto('/dashboard');
await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle'); // Waits for network to settle

// Playwright auto-waits for element to be visible, enabled, and stable
await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit Application' }).click();

// Now wait for next navigation or load state
await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded');
```

✅ Or use `expect().toBeEnabled()` before clicking to assert readiness:
```ts
const submitBtn = page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit Application' });
await expect(submitBtn).toBeEnabled();
await submitBtn.click();
```

❌ Avoid:
```ts
await page.sleep(2000); // ❌ Flaky, non-deterministic
await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 2000)); // ❌ Same issue
```

Best practice: Combine `waitForLoadState()` with role-based locators for predictable timing (SC 2.1.1, SC 2.4.7 compatibility). For dynamic content (e.g., modals), use `waitForSelector()` with `state: 'visible'`:
```ts
await page.waitForSelector('#confirmation-modal', { state: 'visible' });
```

Configure default timeouts in `playwright.config.ts`:
```ts
use: {
  actionTimeout: 10_000, // 10s for all actions
}
```

Use Playwright’s **test fixtures** (`test.extend`) to create reusable setup logic. Here’s a clean pattern for session reuse with authentication:

```ts
// tests/fixtures.ts
import { test as baseTest } from '@playwright/test';

export interface AuthFixture {
  logged-in-user: { username: string; session: string };
}

export const test = baseTest.extend<AuthFixture>({
  logged-in-user: async ({ browser }, use) => {
    const context = await browser.newContext();
    const page = await context.newPage();

    await page.goto('/login');
    await page.getByLabel('Username').fill('demo_user');
    await page.getByLabel('Password').fill('secure_password_123');
    await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Log in' }).click();
    await page.waitForURL('/dashboard');

    const session = await context.storageState();
    await context.close();

    await use({
      username: 'demo_user',
      session: JSON.stringify(session)
    });
  },
});

export const expect = test.expect;
```

Usage in test files:

```ts
// tests/dashboard.spec.ts
import { test } from '../fixtures';

test('user sees dashboard after login', async ({ logged-in-user }) => {
  const context = await test.browser.newContext({
    storageState: JSON.parse(logged-in-user.session)
  });
  const page = await context.newPage();

  await page.goto('/dashboard');
  await expect(page).toHaveURL('/dashboard');
  await expect(page.getByRole('heading', { name: 'Welcome back' })).toBeVisible();
});
```

⚠️ Important: For true parallelization & speed, prefer `test.use()` with `storageState` per worker, not browser reuse. See [Playwright auth docs](https://playwright.dev/docs/auth) for production patterns.

This approach avoids duplicate login code (SC 3.3.2 — labels/instructions consistency) and improves test reliability.

Replace deprecated `page.isVisible()` and `page.isHidden()` with **locator-based assertions**, and combine them with `expect(...).toBeVisible()` or `expect(...).toBeHidden()` — which include built-in waiting and retries.

**Why `page.*` is flaky**: These methods return *immediately* without waiting for the element to appear or become visible/hidden. They also do not respect Playwright’s actionability checks.

**Modern equivalent**:
```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('checks visibility of search results', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/search');
  await page.getByRole('searchbox').fill('health');
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Search' }).click();

  const results = page.getByRole('list', { name: 'Search results' });

  // Waits up to default timeout (5s) for list to become visible
  await expect(results).toBeVisible();

  // Waits for empty results to become hidden
  const emptyMsg = page.getByText('No results found');
  await expect(emptyMsg).toBeHidden();
});
```

**Best practices**:
- Always use `getByRole()`, `getByLabel()`, or `getByText()` to build locators.
- Prefer `expect(locator).toBeVisible()` over manual `await page.isVisible()`.
- Avoid `strict: true` unless you *require* single-element resolution — it can mask upstream selector issues.

This approach aligns with WCAG 4.1.2 (Name, Role, Value) because `getByRole()` validates ARIA semantics.

Use `getByRole('checkbox')` to toggle the checkbox, then assert the button’s `aria-disabled` state or role-specific disabled condition with `expect(button).toBeDisabled()`.

**Example**:
```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('submit button enabled only after checkbox accepted', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/consent-form');

  const checkbox = page.getByRole('checkbox', { name: /I accept the terms/i });
  const submitBtn = page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' });

  // Initially disabled
  await expect(submitBtn).toBeDisabled();

  // Check the box
  await checkbox.check();

  // Now enabled
  await expect(submitBtn).toBeEnabled();

  // Optional: explicitly test aria-disabled for robustness
  await expect(submitBtn).not.hasAttribute('aria-disabled', 'true');
});
```

**Why this matters for accessibility**:
- SC 4.1.2 (Name, Role, Value) requires controls to expose correct states (enabled/disabled).
- SC 2.1.1 (Keyboard) requires all functionality available via keyboard — disabling without visual cue violates perceivable state.
- `toBeEnabled()/toBeDisabled()` assertions validate both ARIA and native HTML behavior.

**Avoid**: `button.hasAttribute('disabled')` alone — it misses `aria-disabled` or CSS-based visual disabling that lacks semantic state.

Use `waitForLoadState('networkidle')` *after* `page.goto()` to ensure network activity settles, then use `getByRole('navigation')` to locate the menu. Combine with explicit assertions to wait for menu items.

**Recommended pattern**:
```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('navigation loads after async fetch', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/home');

  // Wait for network to be idle (no outstanding requests for 500ms)
  await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');

  // Locate navigation *after* load state
  const nav = page.getByRole('navigation');

  // Wait for menu items to appear
  await expect(nav.getByRole('link', { name: 'About' })).toBeVisible();
  await expect(nav.getByRole('link', { name: 'Services' })).toBeVisible();
  await expect(nav.getByRole('link', { name: 'Contact' })).toBeVisible();
});
```

**Key points**:
- `page.goto()` only waits for `load` event — not necessarily when *all* JS finishes or API calls resolve.
- `waitForLoadState('networkidle')` is safer for SPAs or dynamic pages.
- `getByRole('navigation')` validates ARIA semantics (SC 1.3.1, 1.3.2) and is more robust than CSS selectors.
- Avoid `setTimeout()` or `page.waitForTimeout()` — they are non-deterministic and flaky.

**Alternative** (if network state is unreliable):
```ts
await page.waitForSelector('[data-menu-loaded]', { state: 'visible' });
```
but prefer `waitForLoadState()` first.

Use locator-based APIs instead of deprecated page methods, and assert with `toBeChecked()`.

✅ Recommended:
```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('checkbox can be checked', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/form');

  const consentCheckbox = page.getByRole('checkbox', { name: 'I consent to data processing' });
  await expect(consentCheckbox).not.toBeChecked();

  await consentCheckbox.click();
  await expect(consentCheckbox).toBeChecked();
});
```

Key points:
- `getByRole('checkbox', { name: '…' })` is WCAG-friendly and robust
- Use `expect(locator).toBeChecked()` instead of `await page.isChecked()`
- Avoid `page.setChecked()` — it’s discouraged in Playwright v1.40+
- Clicking the locator triggers native browser behavior, including label association

⚠️ Never use `getByLabel()` alone for state assertions — it matches labels but not the input element directly.

Strict mode errors occur when Playwright expects one element but finds multiple. In WCAG-compliant UIs, this often means duplicate roles lack unique accessible names.

✅ Fix by adding more precise locator criteria:
```ts
// ❌ Fails if multiple buttons share 'Submit'
const submitBtn = page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' });

// ✅ Use context or unique text:
const submitBtn = page.locator('form#registration').getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' });
// or
const submitBtn = page.getByRole('button', { name: /Submit application/i });
```

✅ Or disable strict mode (not recommended unless unavoidable):
```ts
const submitBtn = page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' }, { strict: false });
await submitBtn.first().click();
```

🔍 WCAG connection: Duplicate buttons with identical accessible names violate SC 4.1.2 (Name, Role, Value) because assistive tech cannot distinguish them. Fix the UI first — only fall back to `strict: false` as a temporary test workaround.

Use `expect(locator).toBeVisible()` or `toBeEnabled()` *before* interacting. Playwright auto-waits for actionability, but explicit waits improve debugging and WCAG compliance verification.

✅ Robust pattern:
```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('fill dynamic field', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/dynamic-form');

  // Wait for the field to appear
  const emailField = page.getByLabel('Email address', { exact: true });
  await expect(emailField).toBeVisible();
  await expect(emailField).toBeEnabled();

  await emailField.fill('user@gov.example.org');
  await expect(emailField).toHaveValue('user@gov.example.org');
});
```

✅ Or chain with `waitFor` (legacy, but still valid):
```ts
await page.waitForSelector('input[name="email"]', { state: 'attached' });
await page.fill('input[name="email"]', 'user@gov.example.org');
```

🔍 WCAG note:
- SC 3.3.2 (Labels or Instructions) requires visible labels — using `getByLabel` aligns with this.
- `toBeVisible()` verifies the field is perceivable before interaction (SC 1.3.1 Info and Relationships).
- Avoid `force: true` — it bypasses accessibility checks and may interact with hidden elements.

Use **`locator.fill()`** — it's the recommended modern pattern in Playwright for form field interaction.

✅ Correct (modern, robust, WCAG-aware):
```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('fills email field', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/contact');

  const emailInput = page.getByLabel('Email Address');
  await emailInput.fill('user@example.gov');
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' }).click();

  await expect(page).toHaveURL(/.*confirmation/);
});
```

❌ Avoid (deprecated or discouraged):
- `page.type()` — sends low-level key events; only for special keyboard handling
- `page.fill(selector)` — still works, but locator-based is preferred for test stability and accessibility awareness

**Why `locator.fill()`?**
- Automatically waits for actionability (visible, enabled, stable)
- Triggers the same events as user input
- Works with role-based locators (`getByLabel`, `getByPlaceholder`, etc.)
- Compatible with Playwright’s built-in retry logic and timeouts

For WCAG 2.2 AA compliance:
- Ensure your form labels are properly associated with inputs (`for`/`id` or `aria-label`/`aria-labelledby`)
- Use `getByLabel()` instead of brittle CSS selectors — this also validates label presence during test execution

Two best practices to fix flaky tests: **1)** use `page.waitForLoadState()` before interactions, and **2)** set appropriate timeouts via `setDefaultTimeout()` or per-action options.

✅ Robust test pattern:
```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('submits form reliably', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/report');

  // Wait for DOM to be fully loaded and network idle
  await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');

  // Optional: set custom timeout for this action
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Download PDF' }).click({
    timeout: 15_000 // 15 seconds
  });
});
```

✅ Global timeout configuration (`playwright.config.ts`):
```ts
import { defineConfig } from '@playwright/test';

export default defineConfig({
  use: {
    actionTimeout: 10_000,  // default for actions like click, fill
    navigationTimeout: 30_000
  }
});
```

⚠️ Avoid `page.waitForSelector()` — it’s outdated. Playwright locators auto-retry (up to timeout). Use `waitForLoadState()` to ensure page readiness *before* interacting.

**WCAG 2.2 AA alignment:**
- `waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded')` or `'networkidle'` helps avoid race conditions where assistive tech might miss dynamic content
- Timeout settings prevent indefinite hangs that could confuse users relying on predictable interactions

Bonus: For SPAs (e.g., React/Angular), prefer `'networkidle'` to ensure all AJAX calls settle.

Use **`getByLabel()` for accessibility-aware locators**, and Playwright’s built-in `check()`/`uncheck()` on locators (not deprecated `page.*` methods). Leverage fixtures for test isolation.

✅ Full test with `test.beforeEach` and fixtures:
```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

const FIXTURE_EMAIL = 'tester@example.gov';

test('terms checkbox behavior', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/register');

  const termsCheckbox = page.getByLabel('I agree to the terms');

  // Verify unchecked by default
  await expect(termsCheckbox).not.toBeChecked();

  // Check the box
  await termsCheckbox.check();
  await expect(termsCheckbox).toBeChecked();

  // Fill required field and submit
  await page.getByLabel('Email Address').fill(FIXTURE_EMAIL);
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Register' }).click();

  // Assert redirection or success message
  await expect(page).toHaveURL(/.*welcome/);
});
```

✅ With `test.beforeEach` to reset state (e.g., in a reusable fixture):
```ts
// In helpers.ts or playwright.config.ts
import { test as base } from '@playwright/test';

export const test = base.extend<{ resetCheckbox: void }>({
  resetCheckbox: async ({ page }, use) => {
    await use();
    // Cleanup: uncheck if needed for repeat tests
    const checkbox = page.getByLabel('I agree to the terms');
    if (await checkbox.isChecked()) {
      await checkbox.uncheck();
    }
  }
});
```

**Critical notes:**
- ✅ Use `locator.check()` / `locator.uncheck()` — modern, actionability-aware
- ❌ Avoid `page.check()` / `page.uncheck()` — deprecated (use locators instead)
- ✅ Always assert with `expect(locator).toBeChecked()` — it’s WCAG-aware (checks real DOM state)

**WCAG 2.2 AA alignment:**
- Using `getByLabel()` ensures the label exists and is properly associated (SC 1.3.1, 4.1.2)
- Avoiding `trial: true` or `force: true` preserves actionability checks (SC 2.1.1, 4.1.3)

Use the `goto()` method’s built-in `waitUntil` option or `waitForLoadState()` after navigation. The recommended approach is to rely on `page.goto()`’s default `waitUntil: 'load'` behavior and then assert visibility using locators or assertions — no explicit waits needed.

✅ Recommended pattern:
```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('navigates and verifies content', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org');
  await expect(page.getByRole('main')).toBeVisible();
});
```

If you must wait explicitly (e.g., after a form post that triggers a redirect), use:
```ts
await page.goto('/submit', { waitUntil: 'networkidle' });
// or
await page.goto('/submit');
await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');
```

⚠️ Avoid:
- `page.waitForSelector()` — discouraged per Playwright docs
- `page.waitForTimeout()` — flaky and never appropriate in tests
- Manual `setTimeout()` wrappers

Locators and `expect().toBeVisible()` assertions **automatically wait** up to the test timeout (default 5s), making explicit waits unnecessary in most cases.

Set global timeouts in `playwright.config.ts` via `use` options, and override selectively in tests using `page.setDefaultTimeout()` or `page.setDefaultNavigationTimeout()`.

✅ Global config (`playwright.config.ts`):
```ts
import { defineConfig } from '@playwright/test';

export default defineConfig({
  use: {
    actionTimeout: 10_000,      // For click, fill, type, etc.
    navigationTimeout: 30_000,  // For goto(), waitForURL(), etc.
  },
});
```

✅ Per-page override (within a test):
```ts
test('high-latency environment', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.setDefaultNavigationTimeout(60_000);
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/slow-endpoint');
});
```

⚠️ Important:
- `actionTimeout` covers `click()`, `fill()`, `expect().toBeVisible()` (via locators)
- `navigationTimeout` covers `goto()`, `waitForURL()`, `frameNavigation()`
- Never rely on `browserContext.setDefaultTimeout()` unless sharing context across tests (uncommon)

✅ Best practice: Use short global timeouts (5–15s) to catch regressions early, and increase only when necessary (e.g., third-party iframes).

Use `getByRole()` with appropriate roles and `getByRole('link')` for menu items. Playwright’s role-based locators are rooted in ARIA semantics and align with WCAG 2.2 AA success criteria like 1.3.1, 2.4.6, and 4.1.2.

✅ Example test (`nav.test.ts`):
```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('main navigation is accessible and visible', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org');

  // Get the navigation landmark
  const nav = page.getByRole('navigation', { name: 'Main' });
  await expect(nav).toBeVisible();

  // Verify at least one menu item is present and visible
  const menuItems = nav.getByRole('link');
  await expect(menuItems).toHaveCount(4);
  await expect(menuItems.nth(0)).toBeVisible();
});
```

🔍 Tips:
- Use `{ name: '…' }` to disambiguate multiple nav elements (e.g., `{ name: 'Footer' }`)
- Prefer `getByRole('navigation')` over `getByTestId()` or CSS selectors
- To verify labels: `expect(nav).toHaveAttribute('aria-label', 'Main navigation')`

✅ WCAG alignment:
- `1.3.1 Info and Relationships` → semantic nav role
- `2.4.6 Headings and Labels` → clear nav labels
- `4.1.2 Name, Role, Value` → correct ARIA roles

No timeouts or waits needed — assertions auto-retry until pass or timeout.

Create `playwright.config.ts` in your project root with the following minimal configuration:

```ts
import { defineConfig, devices } from '@playwright/test';

export default defineConfig({
  testDir: './tests',
  fullyParallel: true,
  retries: process.env.CI ? 2 : 0,
  workers: 1,
  timeout: 30_000,
  use: {
    baseURL: 'https://agency.example.org',
    trace: 'on-first-retry',
  },

  projects: [
    {
      name: 'webkit',
      use: { ...devices['Desktop WebKit'] },
    },
    {
      name: 'firefox',
      use: { ...devices['Desktop Firefox'] },
    },
  ],
});
```

**Notes:**
- `baseURL` should reflect your local or staging environment (e.g., `http://localhost:8000` during dev).
- Use `devices['Desktop Firefox']` and `devices['Desktop WebKit']` for browser parity with Chrome/Firefox/WebKit desktop.
- Run tests with `npx playwright test`.
- For accessibility testing, combine with `@axe-core/playwright` in your test cases.

Ensure Playwright browsers are installed via `npx playwright install --with-deps`.

Use `getByLabel` for form fields and `getByRole('button', { name })` for submission — these locators align with how assistive technologies perceive controls and include built-in auto-waiting.

Example test (`tests/login.spec.ts`):

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('user can log in', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('/user/login');

  // Auto-waits for label to be visible and associated input ready
  await page.getByLabel('Username or Email').fill('jane.doe');
  await page.getByLabel('Password').fill('correct-horse-battery-staple');

  // Locate submit button by visible text + role
  await expect(page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Log in' })).toBeVisible();
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Log in' }).click();

  // Wait for navigation to complete
  await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');

  expect(page.url()).toContain('/user');
});
```

**Key principles:**
- `getByLabel` binds to `<label for="...">` or implicit `<label>` wrapping — robust to DOM re-renders.
- `getByRole('button', { name })` is preferred over `getByText('Log in')` because it validates semantic role *and* accessible name.
- Avoid CSS selectors (`#edit-name`) — they break on theme changes or ARIA updates.

For multi-step forms, chain `frameLocator` or `getByRole` with filters like `{ disabled: false }`.

Use `page.waitForLoadState('networkidle')` *after* navigation, and combine with `expect(locator).toBeVisible()` for element-specific readiness.

Example:

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('shows success message after form submit', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('/contact');
  await page.getByLabel('Your message').fill('Hello, world!');
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Send message' }).click();

  // Wait for all network requests to settle (e.g., AJAX, CSS/JS, fonts)
  await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');

  // Now assert visibility — Playwright auto-retries for up to `timeout` ms
  await expect(
    page.getByRole('status', { name: 'Your message has been sent.' })
  ).toBeVisible();
});
```

**Load-state options:**
- `'domcontentloaded'` — DOM is ready (earlier, not always sufficient for JS-driven content)
- `'load'` — All resources (including images) loaded
- `'networkidle'` — No ongoing network connections (best for SPAs/Drupal AJAX forms)

**Pro tip:** Prefer `waitForLoadState('networkidle')` over `setTimeout` or `page.waitForTimeout()` — the latter is flaky and violates WCAG 2.2 timing fairness (SC 2.2.1, 2.2.4).

Here is a correct Playwright test using `frameLocator` and `getByRole` for WCAG-compliant element access:

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('Sign in button inside iframe is accessible by role', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/login');
  await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');

  const frameLocator = page.frameLocator('#auth-frame');
  const signInButton = frameLocator.getByRole('button', { name: 'Sign in' });

  await expect(signInButton).toBeVisible();
  await expect(signInButton).toBeEnabled();
  await signInButton.click();

  // Optional: verify navigation or state change
  await expect(page).toHaveURL(/.*\/dashboard/);
});
```

Key points:
- `frameLocator()` isolates the iframe context without needing `switchToFrame()`
- `getByRole('button', { name: 'Sign in' })` uses implicit HTML role and accessible name — ideal for assistive technology parity
- `toBeVisible()` and `toBeEnabled()` verify basic accessibility states
- Never use CSS/XPath chains inside iframes; prefer role + accessible name

This approach aligns with WCAG 2.2 AA principles: perceivable (visible), operable (clickable), and robust (role-based interaction).

Set the `testIdAttribute` in your Playwright config (`playwright.config.ts`):

```ts
import { defineConfig } from '@playwright/test';

export default defineConfig({
  use: {
    testIdAttribute: 'data-pw',
  },
});
```

Then in your HTML, use `data-pw`:

```html
<button data-pw="submit-form">Submit</button>
```

And in your tests:

```ts
await page.getByTestId('submit-form').click();
```

⚠️ **Best practice**: Prefer user-facing locators first (`getByRole`, `getByLabel`) over test IDs. Reserve `data-pw`/`getByTestId` for elements without reliable semantics or labels (e.g., dynamic list items, complex widgets).

This config change is global across all tests in the project and ensures consistency in test ID strategy.

Here's a simple, accessible-first Playwright test using `getByLabel`:

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('email field is accessible and accepts input', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://agency.example.org/contact');
  await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');

  const emailInput = page.getByLabel('Email');

  await expect(emailInput).toBeVisible();
  await expect(emailInput).toHaveAttribute('type', 'email');
  await emailInput.fill('test@gov.example.org');

  // Verify the value was accepted
  await expect(emailInput).toHaveValue('test@gov.example.org');

  // Optional: submit and assert success message
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: /submit/i }).click();
  await expect(page.getByText('Message sent')).toBeVisible();
});
```

✅ Why this meets WCAG 2.2 AA:
- `getByLabel('Email')` uses the accessible name defined by the `<label>` — how screen readers announce the control (SC 1.3.1, 4.1.2)
- `toHaveAttribute('type', 'email')` ensures native validation and mobile keyboard optimization (SC 3.3.2)
- No fragile DOM-based selectors (resilient to layout changes)

Avoid `getByPlaceholder` or `input[name='email']` — they don’t reflect user-facing semantics.

