Here’s a minimal, best-practice Playwright test using `@playwright/test` and WCAG-aware selectors:

```ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('page loads with h1 heading', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('/about');
  await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');

  const h1 = page.getByRole('heading', { level: 1 });
  await expect(h1).toBeVisible();
  await expect(h1).toHaveText('About Our Agency');
});
```

Key points:
- `getByRole('heading', { level: 1 })` uses [role-based locators](https://playwright.dev/docs/next/locators#locate-by-role), which align with WCAG 2.2 SC 1.3.1 (Info and Relationships) by relying on semantic HTML.
- `waitForLoadState('networkidle')` waits until network activity settles — safer than arbitrary `waitForTimeout`.
- Use `toBeVisible()` over `toHaveCount(1)` to confirm visibility and accessibility relevance.
- All imports come strictly from `@playwright/test`.

Avoid raw CSS selectors like `h1` when a role-based locator is available — they ignore ARIA overrides and improve test resilience.

